 ## 3. Design
+
+### 3.0 Alternative considered: termination as a separate lifecycle concern
+
+Codex review on this plan (round 3) flagged that termination is
+qualitatively different from the four 12a-2 operational decision
+types: those four are homogeneous orchestrator actions
+(create / dispatch / integrate); termination mutates experiment
+state, gates other decisions, has both policy-driven and
+operator-driven invocation paths, and survives by special-casing
+integration. The reviewer's concrete suggestion was to model
+termination as a separate **experiment-lifecycle gate** outside
+the §6.2 decision-type enumeration entirely.
+
+**Why we keep termination as a §6.2 entry anyway:**
+
+1. **Decision-loop locus.** The orchestrator is already the
+   actor that decides what to do each iteration. Termination is
+   a decision the orchestrator makes (whether to consult a
+   policy and, given the policy's answer, whether to transition
+   experiment state). Putting it in §6.2 keeps the loop's
+   decision-making in one place — a reader looking at "what does
+   the orchestrator decide each iteration?" sees the full list.
+
+2. **`dispatch_mode` reuse.** 12a-2's `dispatch_mode` toggle
+   already gates the four operational decisions per-experiment.
+   Termination sharing the same gating mechanism (a 5th key) is
+   simpler than introducing a parallel `lifecycle_mode` toggle
+   that would only ever have one entry in v0.
+
+3. **Asymmetry is acknowledged, not hidden.** The §6.2 sketch in
+   §3.1 below explicitly calls out that termination is consulted
+   FIRST (before the four operational decisions), and that on
+   `Terminate` only the integration decision continues to run.
+   The asymmetry is documented in spec text, not glossed over.
+
+**What the alternative would look like.** Chapter 03 would have
+§6 (orchestrator role with four operational decisions per 12a-2)
+and a new §7 (experiment-lifecycle gate, listing the termination
+policy and the two paths to invoke it). The decision-loop pseudo
+in §3.5 would split into "lifecycle gate phase" + "operational
+decision phase". The implementation would still sequence the same
+ops; only the spec organization differs.
+
+We pick the §6.2 placement because (1) and (2) outweigh the
+clarity cost of acknowledging the asymmetry in (3). A future
+revision MAY restructure if a second lifecycle gate appears
+(e.g., a "pause" gate distinct from termination); v0 doesn't
+have one.
 
